                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d437">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/13804: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-12-21T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 21, 1936—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 21—9:04 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>368. Shanghai’s telegram of December 20, 4 p.m., especially paragraph 5.<note
                        n="17" xml:id="d437fn17">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>At my request Dr. Kung undertook on December 19 to send a telegram to Donald as
                    from me asking if latter could make arrangements with the Young Marshal for
                    evacuating American missionaries at Sian. I suggested that this be effected by
                    airplane if possible and that other foreigners be included in the
                    arrangement.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping, Shanghai, Hankow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
